      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":30,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":450,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":450,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk briskly for 90 seconds, then ease into a very comfortable jog. No pressure to hit any pace yet — just let your body wake up.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":24,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":450,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a conversational pace — you should be able to speak full sentences without gasping. Aim for 7:30–8:00 /km. If it feels hard, slow down. There is no such thing as too easy on this run.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease back to a slow jog or brisk walk for the final 3 minutes. Let your heart rate settle before you stop.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start with a 2-minute brisk walk to get blood moving, then ease into your jog gradually. No need to stretch before — save that for after.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"After stopping, do 5 minutes of gentle stretching: calves, quads, hip flexors, and hamstrings. This is your recovery investment.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Welcome to week 1, Sarah! This Monday run is the cornerstone of your aerobic base. At your current fitness level, easy running is genuinely the most productive thing you can do — it builds the capillary network and mitochondrial density your body needs to sustain any faster running later. The goal today is simple: finish feeling like you could have gone further. That feeling means you got the dose exactly right.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Midweek Easy Run with Strides\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":32,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":450,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":390,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk for 90 seconds, then ease into a comfortable jog. Keep it very relaxed.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":22,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":450,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Comfortable conversational pace throughout. This is your bread-and-butter easy effort — 7:00–8:00 /km. Focus on relaxed form: tall posture, relaxed shoulders, light foot strike.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":390,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":4,\"notes\":\"4 x 20-second gentle accelerations (strides) with 40 seconds walking between each. These are NOT sprints — think of them as 'smooth and quick'. Accelerate gradually to about 75% effort and hold for 20 seconds. They teach your legs neuromuscular efficiency without any real fatigue cost.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk or very easy jog for 3 minutes to close out. Let everything settle.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"A gentle walk-to-jog transition is plenty here. Save your energy for the strides at the end of the run.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"5 minutes of post-run stretching. Pay particular attention to calves and hip flexors — these tend to tighten up early in new training blocks.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The strides at the end of this run are a small but meaningful addition. Introducing a little neuromuscular stimulus — brief moments of quicker running — helps your body start learning efficient turnover without any real physiological stress. Think of them as 'teaching your legs to move quickly' rather than speed work. The pace listed for strides (around 6:30 /km) is a guide, not a rule — go by feel and smoothness.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Weekend Long Run\",\"target_distance_km\":6,\"target_duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":465,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":465,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk 2 minutes, then ease into a gentle jog. The long run should feel almost embarrassingly easy at the start.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":39,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":465,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Steady, easy effort throughout — 7:30–8:00 /km. If you find yourself breathing harder than conversational, slow down. The goal of the long run is time on feet, not pace. Your aerobic system is building with every minute you spend at this effort.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Slow to a walk for the final 3 minutes. You have earned this.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Take it genuinely easy for the first kilometre. Long runs build the aerobic engine that makes everything else possible — treating the opening kilometres as a warmup protects that investment.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"After your long run, spend 8–10 minutes stretching. Focus on quads, hamstrings, calves, and glutes. If you have access to a foam roller, your calves and IT band will thank you later in the plan.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is your key workout of the week, Sarah. Your long run builds aerobic capacity, trains your body to burn fat efficiently as fuel, and develops the connective tissue strength that protects you from injury as mileage grows. At 6 km this week — a gentle step up from your current 5 km long run — we are respecting the 10% progression rule. The pace truly does not matter here. Slower is often better on long runs. Finish feeling strong, not depleted.\",\"perceived_effort\":5}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
